The idea is to use both starts and ends as keys, but +1 for a start and -1 for an end as values. So, going by sorted keys and gathering sum of values we will know for sure when current interval finishes (we have + 1 at start and -1 at finish -> 0 when interval finishes). 
In case of overlaps starts will sum up (3 starts crossed -> 3) and eventually at the last finish(3 finishes crossed -> 3 -3 = 0) it became 0 nevertheless. 

Complexity is n(log(n)) due to the nature of tree map.

```
class Solution {
    public int[][] merge(int[][] intervals) {
        List<int[]> list = new LinkedList<>();
        TreeMap<Integer, Integer> map = new TreeMap<>();

        for (int[] interval : intervals) {
            map.put(interval[0], map.getOrDefault(interval[0], 0) + 1);
            map.put(interval[1], map.getOrDefault(interval[1], 0) - 1);
        }

        int activeInterval = 0;
        int start = 0;
        for (int key: map.keySet()) {
            if (activeInterval == 0) {
                start = key;
            }    
            activeInterval += map.get(key);
            if (activeInterval == 0) {
                list.add(new int[]{start, key});
            }
        }

        return listToArray(list);
    }

    private int[][] listToArray(List<int[]> list) {
        int[][] result = new int[list.size()][2];
        for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
            result[i] = list.get(i);
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

