# Approach
- First, the intervals are sorted in ascending order based on their start times using the sort function. This is important for efficient merging.

- A new vector called ans is created to store the merged intervals.

- The solution iterates through each interval in the sorted intervals array.

- If ans is empty or the start time of the current interval is greater than the end time of the last interval in ans, it means there is no overlap. In this case, the current interval is added to ans as a new non-overlapping interval.

- If there is an overlap, the end time of the last interval in ans is updated to be the maximum of the current interval's end time and the end time of the last interval in ans. This ensures that the merged interval covers the maximum range.

- After iterating through all intervals, the function returns the ans vector, which contains the merged non-overlapping intervals.

Overall, the solution works by sorting the intervals based on start times and then merging them iteratively, updating the end time as needed. This approach ensures that all overlapping intervals are merged, resulting in a set of non-overlapping intervals that cover the entire input array.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(nlogn + n)

- Space complexity:
O(1). O(n) to store the answer

