# **Facebook Followup - Stream of Intervals**
**General Question**: What if the data comes as a stream in real time - No meaningful sorting can be done.

Implementation based on Interval based BSTs so that we can `query` multiple times. We also create an `insert` method that we will need for the interval tree.

### Implementation Details & Code 

- `IntervalTree` is the new class that we need to define, and we will use it to define `start`, `end` and `mid` points for each node.
- `insertInterval` method - if the interval to be added touches or crosses the `middle` of the current node, we merge them directly, else we insert the new interval in the `left` or `right` subtree.
```
void insertInterval(IntervalTree *node, Interval *currentInterval) {
    if (currentInterval->end < node->middle) { // Check if the entire interval is included before middle.
        if (node->left) {
            insertInterval(node->left, currentInterval);
        } else {
            IntervalTree *newNode = new IntervalTree(currentInterval->start, currentInterval->end);
            node->left = newNode;
        }
    }
    else if (currentInterval->start > node->middle) { // Check if the entire interval is included after middle.
        if (node->right) {
            insertInterval(node->right, currentInterval);
        } else {
            IntervalTree *newNode = new IntervalTree(currentInterval->start, currentInterval->end);
            node->right = newNode;
        }
    }
    else { // Merge directly if the new interval does not fit before OR after the middle point.
        node->start = min(node->start, currentInterval->start);
        node->end = max(node->end, currentInterval->end);
    }
}
```
- `queryInterval` method - retrieve merged intervals of the `left` subtree, `leftIntervals` and those of the `right` subtree `rightIntervals`. 
```
void queryInterval(vector<Interval *> &retV, IntervalTree *node) { 
    // retV is the collection vector.
    vector<Interval *> leftIntervals;
    vector<Interval *> rightIntervals;

    // Check if we can merge the current node with intervals from the left subtree.
    bool mergeLeft = false; 

    if (node->left) {
        queryInterval(leftIntervals, node->left); // Merge all the intervals in left subtree.
        mergeLeftInterval(leftIntervals, node, retV, mergeLeft); // Find the merge point with the leftIntervals.
    }

    if (!mergeLeft) { // If we didn't merge left, create a new interval.
        Interval *newInterval = new Interval(node->start, node->end);
        retV.push_back(newInterval);
    }

    if (node->right) {
        queryInterval(rightIntervals, node->right); //Merge all the intervals in the right subtree.
        mergeRightInterval(rightIntervals, node, retV); // Find the merge point with the rightIntervals.
    }
}
```
- the two merge methods `mergeLeftInterval` and `mergeRightInterval` are implemented similarly
	- if we find an interval that overlaps with the current `node`, we know that everything after will overlap
	- the first intervals that overlap will be all merged and the rest inserted at the end
```
void mergeLeftInterval(vector<Interval *> &leftIntervals, IntervalTree *node, 
                       vector<Interval *> &retV, bool &merged) {
    for (int i = 0; i < leftIntervals.size(); i++) { 
		// If any of the left intervals intersects with the current interval, we merge it and break.
        if (leftIntervals[i]->end >= node->start) { 
            Interval *newInterval = new Interval(min(leftIntervals[i]->start, node->start), node->end); 
            retV.push_back(newInterval);
            merged = true;
            break;
        } else {
			// Else we push the interval directly.
            retV.push_back(leftIntervals[i]);
        }
    }
}
```
```
void mergeRightInterval(vector<Interval *> &rightIntervals, IntervalTree *node,
                        vector<Interval *> &retV) {
    for (int i = 0; i < rightIntervals.size(); i++) {
        if (rightIntervals[i]->start <= node->end) {
			// We extend the right end of the last appended interval whenever an intersection takes place.
            retV[retV.size() - 1]->end = max(rightIntervals[i]->end, node->end); 
        } else {
			// Else we push the interval directly.
            retV.push_back(rightIntervals[i]); 
        }
    }
}
```

Inspiration comes from this post: https://leetcode.com/problems/merge-intervals/discuss/21452/Share-my-interval-tree-solution-no-sorting

