# Intuition
- First we will check if the array of intervals given is already `sorted or not`.
- If not then we will `sort` it .
- Then we for merging we will check if the `first index of second interval is less than second index of first interval`.
- If the above case satisfies then we will merge them otherwise we will push that interval as it is in the result and use it for further comparison.
- The above logic is more explained in the approaches below.
# Approaches
## 1.Brute Force
- `Sorting` the intervals in ascending order.
- Using `2 loops` for $$iterating$$ and `linear searching of interval`.
- `Outer loop` is for iterating the array .
- `Inner Loop` is for linear search that if the any interval is overlapping with the interval of the current iteration.
### Code
```cpp
vector<vector<int>> merge(vector<vector<int>>& arr) {
    int n = arr.size(); // Get the size of the input vector
    sort(arr.begin(), arr.end()); // Sort the intervals based on their starting points
    vector<vector<int>> ans; // Initialize an empty vector to store the merged intervals

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) { // Iterate through each interval
        int start = arr[i][0], end = arr[i][1];

        // If the last interval in the merged intervals vector overlaps with the current interval, skip the current interval
        if (!ans.empty()) {
            if (start <= ans.back()[1]) {
                continue;
            }
        }

        // Iterate through the remaining intervals and merge overlapping intervals
        for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            if (arr[j][0] <= end) {
                end = max(end, arr[j][1]);
            }
        }

        // Store the merged interval in the answer vector
        end = max(end, arr[i][1]);
        ans.push_back({start, end});
    }

    return ans; // Return the merged intervals
}
```
### Complexity
- **Time Complexity** - $O(NlogN)+O(N*N). O(NlogN)$
- **Space Complexity** - $O(N)$
## 2. Optimal Approach
- Linearly iterate over the array if the data structure is empty insert the interval in the data structure.
- If the last element in the data structure overlaps with the current interval we merge the intervals by updating the last element in the data structure, and if the current interval does not overlap with the last element in the data structure simply insert it into the data structure.
- Since we have sorted the intervals, the intervals which will be merging are bound to be adjacent. 
- We `kept on merging simultaneously` as we were traversing through the array and when the element was non-overlapping we simply inserted the element in our data structure.
### Code
```cpp
vector<vector<int>> merge(vector<vector<int>>& intervals) {
    vector<vector<int>> mergedInterval; // Initialize an empty vector to store merged intervals
    if(intervals.size()==0)
      {
        return mergedInterval;
      }
    sort(intervals.begin(),intervals.end()); // Sort the input intervals based on the start time

    vector<int> tempInterval = intervals[0]; // Initialize a temporary interval with the first interval in the sorted list

    for(auto i:intervals)
    {
        if(i[0]<= tempInterval[1]) // If the current interval's start time is less than or equal to the end time of the temporary interval
        {
            tempInterval[1]=max(i[1],tempInterval[1]); // Update the end time of the temporary interval with the maximum of the end times of current interval and the temporary interval
        }
        else
        {
            mergedInterval.push_back(tempInterval); // If the current interval's start time is greater than the end time of the temporary interval, push the temporary interval into the merged intervals vector
            tempInterval = i; // Update the temporary interval with the current interval
        }
    }
    mergedInterval.push_back(tempInterval); // Push the last temporary interval into the merged intervals vector
    return mergedInterval; // Return the merged intervals vector
}
```
### Complexity
- **Time Complexity -** $O(NlogN) + O(N). O(NlogN)$
- **Space Complexity -** $O(N)$

