So we have to find i , j , k such that    **(nums[i]<nums[j]>nums[k])     where i<j<k.**

The   approach is to  **fix i and j such that we could find a k which satisfies the above condition,**
to fix i and j the approach is  we will loop through the nums array  the current element of the array will be nums[j] now according to the condtion we need to find an element in the prefix of the nums array from current element which is smaller the current element.
for eg - > nums = [ 1,2,3,4,6,5] and we are at 4 so our nums[j] is 4 now we need to find an element in [1,2,3] that is prefix of that array from current position which is smaller than 4.
to do this we will just maintan the smallest element till now.
so now our i and j are fixed we need to find k .
to do this we just put the suffix of nums fromt current position into a multiset and tried to find an element that is larger than nums[i] but smaller the nums[j] using upper bound on the multiset 

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool find132pattern(vector<int>& nums) {
        int mn;
        int n = nums.size();
        if(n<3)
        {
            return 0;
        }
        multiset<int> ms(nums.begin() , nums.end());    
        mn = nums[0];
        ms.erase(ms.find(nums[0]));
        for(int i = 1; i+1 < n ; i++)
        {
            ms.erase(ms.find(nums[i]));
            auto  y = ms.upper_bound(mn);
            if(y == ms.end())
            {
                mn = min(mn , nums[i]);
                continue;
            }
            int z = *y;
            if(z>mn && z<nums[i])
            {
                return 1;
            }
            mn = min(mn , nums[i]);
        }
        return 0;
    }
};
```
