solutions.content:
	the intuitive thing to understand is that for a given j, the best candidate for i would be the minimum one before j
    because it opens up maximum number of possibilities for the element k


    Min[j] represents the smallest element in the range [0...j] {we will see in a moment what happens when nums[j] == Min[j]}
    we are considering all possibilities for the element nums[j] by iterating over the array in reverse direction
    in the stack we are maintain an increasing order from top to bottom

    as soon as you arrive at the element j, pop out all the elements from the stack which are smaller than or equal to  Min[j] {remember the stack is increasing from top to bottom, so as 
    we keep on popping, the elements will keep increasing}

    while(!stk.empty() && stk.top() <= Min[j]) stk.pop();   ---- (1)

    this pops out all the elements from the stack which are smaller than or equal to Min[j] 
    now after we are done with the popping, the element at the top will be the element which is just greater than Min[j]

    Now there are a Few Cases (after we have performed the popping)

    Case 1 - the stack is empty
             in this case, we have no option but to just push the element j into the stack and continue

    Case 2 - The stack is not empty
            Case 2.1 - the top  of the stack is smaller than nums[j] (stk.top() < nums[j])
                        this is the exact condition we are looking for, so simply return true

            Case 2.2 - the top of the stack is greater than equal to nums[j] (stk.top() >= nums[j])
                       Case 2.2.1 - the top of the stack is greater than nums[j]
                                    this is not a 132 pattern, so simply push nums[j] and continue (remember this still maintain a non decreasing order from top to bottom)

                        Case 2.2.2 - the top of the stack is equal to nums[j]
                                     this also means that 132 pattern is not satisfied and we will simply push nums[j] and continue (this still maintain a non decreasing order from top to bottom)

    Now what happens when nums[j] == Min[j]
    Remember as soon as we arrived at the element j, we pooped out all the elements which were lesser than or equal to nums[j], so there is no way that Case 2.1 will be satisfied, so there is no problem 😃

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool find132pattern(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        vector<int> Min(n, INT_MAX);
        Min[0] = nums[0];
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            Min[i] = min(Min[i - 1], nums[i]);
        }

        stack<int> stk;
        for(int j = n - 1; j >= 0; j--) {
            while(!stk.empty() && stk.top() <= Min[j]) stk.pop();
            if(!stk.empty() && stk.top() < nums[j]) return true;
            stk.push(nums[j]);
        }
        return false;
    }
};
