After having gone through the different solutions posted I didn't see anyone use this so posting this just in case it is easier for someone to understand this.

The idea I came up with is to use a self balancing tree which stores the elements to the right of the current number `(j)` which is our `(k)`. Also instead of creating a min array we can update it on the fly by using a min variable `valPrev` which serves as `(i)` .
```
    public boolean find132pattern(int[] nums) {
        int n  = nums.length;
        if (n < 3) return false;

        TreeSet<Integer> ts = new TreeSet<>();
        ts.add(nums[n - 1]);
        int[] greatestSmallerNext = new int[n];
        for (int i = n - 2; i > 0; i--) {            
            Integer lower = ts.lower(nums[i]);
            if (lower != null) greatestSmallerNext[i] = lower;
            else greatestSmallerNext[i] = nums[i];
            ts.add(nums[i]);
        }

        int valPrev = nums[0];
        for (int i = 1; i < n - 1; i++) {
            valPrev = nums[i] < valPrev ? nums[i] : valPrev;
            if (valPrev < greatestSmallerNext[i] && nums[i] > greatestSmallerNext[i]) {
                return true;
            }
        }        
        return false;
    }
```

**Time complexity:** O(nlogn) since retreival from treeset takes log(n) time.
**Space complexity:** O(n). We are only using array of size `n` to store the next greatest smaller element.

