solutions.content:
**Solution1**
`minOnLeft[j]` indicates minimum on the left side of `j` (inclusive). [**this will be our a<sub>i</sub>**]
What we need is some smaller value on left of `j`  (i.e. `minOnLeft[j]`) and some smaller value on right of `j`  but higher than `minOnLeft[j]`.

So we can scan from the back and maintain a stack which just throws away unwanted values i.e. the values that are smaller than even `minOnLeft[j-1]`, then at each `j` [**this will be our a<sub>j</sub>**] we can see if anything remaining on its right in the stack and see if the peek [**this will be our a<sub>k</sub>**] is smaller than `a[j]`

Time = `O(n)`

```
public boolean find132pattern(int[] a) {
        int n = a.length;
        if(n < 3) return false;
        int[] minOnLeft = new int[n];
        minOnLeft[0] = a[0];
        for(int i=1; i < n; i++)
            minOnLeft[i] = Math.min(a[i], minOnLeft[i-1]);
        Stack<Integer> s = new Stack<>();
        for(int j=n-1; j > 0; j--){
            if(minOnLeft[j-1] < a[j]){
                while(!s.isEmpty() && a[s.peek()] <= minOnLeft[j-1])
                    s.pop();
                if(!s.isEmpty() && a[s.peek()] < a[j])
                    return true;
                s.push(j);
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
```
**Solution2**
`minOnLeft[j]` indicates minimum on the left side of `j` (inclusive).
Now, if we mantain a `bst` coming from right, we can search for an element bigger than `minOnLeft[j-1]` in the sorted numbers from bst after `a[j]`.

Time = `O(n lgn)`

```
public boolean find132pattern(int[] a) {
        int n = a.length;
        if(n < 3) return false;
        int[] minOnLeft = new int[n];
        TreeSet<Integer> bst = new TreeSet<>();
        minOnLeft[0] = a[0];
        for(int i=1; i < n; i++)
            minOnLeft[i] = Math.min(a[i], minOnLeft[i-1]);
        bst.add(a[n-1]);
        for(int j=n-2; j > 0; j--){
            TreeSet<Integer> tSet = (TreeSet<Integer>)bst.headSet(a[j]);
            if(!tSet.isEmpty() && tSet.higher(minOnLeft[j-1]) != null)
                return true;
            bst.add(a[j]);
        }
        return false;
    }
```

